================================================================================
Interoperability and the firmware authentication key (17 U.S.C. § 1201(f))
================================================================================

Seestar firmware 7.18+ requires an RSA challenge-response handshake to accept
commands. This project:

  * ships NO ZWO firmware, NO ZWO application code, and NO interoperability key;
  * contains NO tool that extracts, derives, or circumvents any key; and
  * does not perform the handshake itself — it drives the external `seestar_alp`
    service, which owns the handshake.

To operate against real 7.18+ hardware, the USER supplies their own key file
(e.g. `seestar_client_key.pem`), extracted by the user from their own lawfully
licensed copy of the ZWO application for the sole purpose of interoperability,
as permitted under the reverse-engineering provision of 17 U.S.C. § 1201(f)
(and analogous provisions elsewhere). That key is a user-supplied secret; it
lives only in the gitignored `secrets/` directory or a `SEESTAR_SECRET_*`
environment variable and is never committed. Users are responsible for
compliance with the laws of their own jurisdiction.

================================================================================
Third-party software this project drives but does NOT vendor or distribute
================================================================================

This repository invokes the following software as separate, user-installed
programs (over a network API or as a subprocess). None of it is bundled,
vendored, statically or dynamically linked into, or redistributed by this
project; each remains under its own license and must be obtained by the user
from its own source.

  * seestar_alp — https://github.com/smart-underworld/seestar_alp
      Primarily GPL-3.0 (with MIT/BSD-3-Clause components). Driven ONLY as a
      separate process over its local ASCOM Alpaca HTTP API (127.0.0.1:5555);
      no seestar_alp source is included or linked here. Operators should pin it
      to a reviewed release.

  * pixinsight-mcp — https://github.com/aescaffre/pixinsight-mcp
      MIT. The optional PixInsight finish hands off to this external server,
      which is the user's own install (macOS-tested; Windows unverified).

  * DeepSkyStacker — https://deepskystacker.free.fr
      Freeware (not open source). Driven via its command-line executable
      (`DeepSkyStackerCL`); not bundled or redistributed.

  * PixInsight — https://pixinsight.com
      Commercial software, separately licensed by the user; only invoked if the
      user has installed it.

